FTIR spectra were also used to confirm the interaction between MnTAPP and GQDs (Fig. 5
                           ). The FTIR spectrum of GQDs showed sharp peaks at 1674 cm−1 and 1397 cm−1 which correspond to the CO stretching and CO stretching of carboxylic acid. The peak appearing at 3216 cm−1 belongs to OH and the CH stretching appeared at 2918 cm−1 
                           [28]. The peaks appearing at 3312 cm−1 and 3187 cm−1 on the FTIR spectrum of the MnTAPP corresponds to the symmetric and asymmetric vibration of NH2. The stretching peak at 1590 cm−1 corresponds to the vibration of CC and CN. The peak appearing at 1558 cm−1 is the bending vibration of NH2 group [29]. The FTIR spectrum of MnTAPP@GQDs showed a shift of the bending vibration of NH2 from 1558 cm−1 (of MnTAPP) to 1521 cm−1. The broadening and shifting of the vibration of CC and CN peak from 1590 cm−1 (of MnTAPP) to 1731 cm−1 (of MnTAPP@GQDs) was observed and there was an appearance of a new peak at 1619 cm−1, due to the amide bond. We could conclude that the linkage was successful for MnTAPP@GQDs. It is also known that shifts in IR bands confirm structural changes [30]. As was the case with XPS, there were no differences in FT-IR spectra for the non-covalently attached MnTAPP--GQDs compared to MnTAPP since there are no new bonds.
